I. Context

Structure

Cortical Bone is a complex, highly organized hard, and lightweight tissue defined by an hierarchy of microstructures ranging from haversian systems, osteons, to elementary minerals.

From a mechanical point-of-view, it is defined as a two-phase composite material: a soft phase mainly containing pores of organic fluid and soft tissues embedded in hidroxyapatite and collagen compound.

Mesoscale

Porosity is distributed over various length scales, nevertheless the main components preponderant to the mechanical behaviour are defined in the range size between $50-200 [\mu m]$.

  • Haversian Canals $\sim 50 [\mu m]$
  • Resorption Cavities $\sim 50-200 [\mu m]$

Observed mesoscale microstructure

Models generated from real $\mu$-CT images provided from Minonzio et. al. 2018

Ultrasound Techniques

Minonzio et al., 2018 developed a QUS procedure to assess bone quality, by retrieving two relevant parameters of bone quality: cortical porosity and thickness.

The methods describes a lower-cost procedure, with non-invasive nor radiative nature challenging methods such as DXA or QCT.

It is expected to reach gold-standard predictions, but wider validation must be obtained and robustness reseach must be taken in consideration.

Schematic description of the experimental procedure and idealization of the macroscopic domain with their characteristic microstructure.

Signal Processing

  1. Each cycle of measurements consist of a sequential excitation of $N^{E} > 0$ emitters, which yield $N^{E}\times N^{R}$ time series array.
  2. The multi-channel signal generated by the excitation of each emitter $m \in \{1,\dots, N^{E}\}$ denoted by $s_m(t,\mathbf{x})$ at fixed time $t$ and receptor position $\mathbf{x}$ is Fourier transformed to frequency domain $S_m(f,\mathbf{x})$ at fixed $f \in \mathbb{R}_+$ related to discretization bandwidth of $N^F>0$ steps.
  3. The spectral description of the recorded wave-front allows a comparison to Lamb-curves by SVD over the signal $S_n(f,\mathbf{x})_{n \in [N^E]}$ in the form: \begin{equation} S_n = U_n \sigma_n D_n \quad n \in \{1,\dots, N^E\} \end{equation}
  4. The singular value bases $(U_n)_n$ then allows to define function on the $(f,k) \in \mathbb{R}_+^2$ space: \begin{equation} L_N(f,k) = \sum_{n=1}^N \left \vert \langle U_n(f, \mathbf{x}) \, \vert \, e^{ik\mathbf{x}} \rangle \right \vert^2 \end{equation} being $0< N\leq N^E$ the mode number intensity.
  5. Since the wave-number $k$ is dependent of the material properties as $(Th, Po)$ then it arises the experimentally obtained wave-modes $L_N(f,k(Po,Th))$, enabling comparison to references.

Parameter recuperation

The parameter recuperation is defined as by the Lamb-wave fitting to the experimentally recorded signal. Explicitely described in the form: \begin{equation} (Po^*, Th^*) = \underset{(Po,Th)\in \mathcal{A}}{\text{argmax }} \int_{f_{min}}^{f_{max}} \frac{1}{M} \sum_{m=1}^M L_N(f, k_m(Po, Th)) \, df \end{equation} being $M>0$ the number of modes and $\mathcal{A}$ the space of porosity $\times$ thickness pairs.

II. Objectives

On this thesis

  • Review of Homogenization.
  • Study of porosity continuity and viscoelasticity.
  • Solve Cell Problems on 2D and 3D.
  • Simulate 2-dimensional models.
  • Extend simulations to 3-dimensions.

III. Theoretical Review

Literature

Hypothesis and Scale Separation

  1. The composite material is modelled by a bounded domain $\Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^d$, asumming the decomposition $\partial \Omega = \Gamma_D \dot \cup \Gamma_N$.
  2. Let $0 < \epsilon \ll 1$ denote the aspect ratio between the macroscopic variable $\mathbf{x} \in \Omega$ and the microscopic one $\mathbf{y} = \frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon} \in \mathbf{Y}$ being $Y = (0,1)^d$ the cell structure characterized by a hard $\mathbf{Y}_m$ and soft $\mathbf{Y}_f$ phase.
  3. The material coefficients are defined then for $i,j,k,l \in \{1,\dots, d\}$ by: \begin{equation} C_{ijkl}(\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon}) = C_{ijkl}(\mathbf{y}) \text{ for } \frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon} = \mathbf{x}_{\mathbf{T}_{\epsilon}(\mathbf{x})} + \mathbf{y}, \mathbf{x} \in \Omega_1^{\epsilon} \end{equation} being $C_{ijkl}(\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon}) = C^m_{ijkl}$ if $\mathbf{x} \in \overline{\Omega}\setminus \Omega_1^{\epsilon}$.

Idealization of the periodic domain microstructure following a square microstructure and each scale.

Formalization

Given $\epsilon >0$, let us fix $p \in (0,1)$, consider $C_{ijkl}^{\epsilon}(\mathbf{x}):= C_{ijkl}(\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon})$ an elastic tensor, $\rho^{\epsilon}(\mathbf{x}) = \rho(\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon})$ a uniformly bounded density and for fixed parameter $T>0$ the following evolution PDE problem: \[ (P) \left \{ \begin{aligned} \rho^{\epsilon} \partial_{tt} u^{\epsilon} - \nabla \cdot \sigma^{\epsilon}(u^{\epsilon}) = \mathbf{0} & \text{ in } (0,T)\times \Omega \\ \sigma^{\epsilon}_{ij}(u^{\epsilon}) = C^{\epsilon}_{ijkl} \mathbf{e}_{kl}(u^{\epsilon}) & \text{ in } (0,T)\times \Omega \\ u^{\epsilon} = \mathbf{0} & \text{ on } (0,T)\times \Gamma_D \\ \sigma^{\epsilon}_{ij}(u^{\epsilon})n_j = \mathbf{F} & \text{ on } (0,T) \times \Gamma_N \\ \partial_{t} u^{\epsilon} = u^{\epsilon} = \mathbf{0} & \text{ on } \{t=0\} \times \Omega \end{aligned} \right . \]

Notation. By denoting in bold d-dimensional function spaces such as $\mathbf{L}^2(\Omega), \, \mathbf{H}^1(\Omega)$. It is defined \begin{equation} \mathbf{H}^1(\Omega, \Gamma_D) = \{ v\in \mathbf{H}^1(\Omega) \, \vert \, \gamma(v) \vert_{\Gamma_D} = \mathbf{0} \} \end{equation}

Inspired from the work of Raviart, (1983):
Proposition. Assuming $0 < \rho_0 \leq \rho(\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon}) < +\infty$ and $\mathbf{F} \in L^{\infty}(0,T;\mathbf{L}^2(\Omega, \Gamma_N))$, there exist a unique solution $u^{\epsilon}$ to $(P)$ for each $\epsilon >0$ such that: \begin{equation} u^{\epsilon} \in \mathcal{C}^0(0,T;\mathbf{H}^1(\Omega, \Gamma_D)) \cap \mathcal{C}^1(0,T;\mathbf{L}^2(\Omega)) \end{equation}

Inspired from the works of Oleinik (1992)
Proposition Assuming that $F \in L^{\infty}(0,T; \mathbf{L}^2(\Gamma_N))$ and also $N^q \in L^{\infty}(0,T;\mathbf{H}^1(\Omega))$ for each $q \in \{1,\dots,d\}$. Then the convergence of solutions is obtained: \begin{equation} \Vert u^{\epsilon} - u^{0} - \epsilon \mathbf{N}^s (\frac{\mathbf{x}}{\epsilon})\partial_{x_s}u^0 \Vert_{L^{\infty}(0,T;\mathbf{H}^1(\Omega, \Gamma_D))} \lesssim \epsilon^{1/2}\Vert u^{0} \Vert_{L^{\infty}(0,T;\mathbf{H}^3(\Omega))} \end{equation}

III. Theoretical Review

Contribution

Contribution

On the Porosity

Continuity on the Porosity

The definition of homogenized coefficients contain an explicit dependency of the porosity level, arising a natural question of continuity.

  • The interest is on bounded, coercive tensors. To this end, let $(\alpha, \beta)$, then a tensor $\mathbf{C} = (C_{ijkl})_{ijkl} \in \mathcal{T}(\alpha, \beta, (0,1)\times \mathbf{Y})$ it satisfies
    1. If $\xi \in \mathbb{R}^{d\times d} \setminus \{\mathbf{0}\}$ then $\alpha \xi_{ij} \xi_{ij} \leq C_{ijkl}(p, \mathbf{y}) \xi_{kl}\xi_{ij} \text{ a.e. } \mathbf{y} \in \mathbf{Y}$.
    2. If $\xi \in \mathbb{R}^{d\times d}\setminus \{ \mathbf{0} \}$ then $\vert C_{ijkl}(p, \mathbf{y}) \xi_{kl} \xi_{ij} \vert \leq \beta \xi_{ij} \xi_{ij} \text{ a.e. } \mathbf{y} \in \mathbf{Y}$.

  • In what follows, it is denoted by $M(\mathbf{Y})$ the space of $d\times d$ matrices of $L^2(\mathbf{Y})$ entries with norm $\Vert \cdot \Vert_{M(\mathbf{Y})}$ defined for $A = (A_{kl})_{kl} \in M(\mathbf{Y})$ by \begin{equation} \Vert A \Vert_{M(\mathbf{Y})} = \big(\sum_{k,l=1}^d \Vert A_{kl} \Vert_{L^2(\mathbf{Y})}^2\big)^{1/2} \end{equation}

From the Heuristic

  • The homogenized coefficients on a unitary cell at porosity level $p \in (0,1)$ are given by: \begin{equation} C^{hom}_{ijrs}(p) = \int_{\mathbf{Y}}C_{ijrs}(p,\mathbf{y}) : m_{rs} + \mathbf{e}\big(\mathbf{N}^{rs}): m_{ij}\, d\mathbf{y} \end{equation} being $\big( \mathbf{N}^{rs}\big)_{rs}$ the cell-solutions where $:$ denotes the contraction of indices.
  • Denoting $(m_{ij})_{ij}$ a base of $d\times d$ matrices, a symmetric description can be obtained: \begin{equation} C^{hom}_{ijrs}(p) = \int_{\mathbf{Y}} \mathbf{C}(p,\mathbf{y}): (m_{rs} + \mathbf{e}(\mathbf{N}^{rs})): (m_{ij} + \mathbf{e}(\mathbf{N}^{ij})) \, d\mathbf{y} \end{equation}

About the Continuity

  • Let $p, q \in (0,1)$ denote two porosity levels. One seeks to estimate: \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} C^{hom}_{ijrs}(p) - C^{hom}_{ijrs}(q) & = \int_{\mathbf{Y}} \mathbf{C}(p) - \mathbf{C}(q): m_{rs} + \mathbf{e}(\mathbf{N}^{rs}(p)): m_{ij} \\ & + \int_{\mathbf{Y}} \mathbf{C}(q):\mathbf{e}(\mathbf{N}^{rs}(p)) - \mathbf{e}(\mathbf{N}^{rs}(q)):m_{ij} \end{aligned} \end{equation}
  • By using the cell problem and coercivity conditions on the elastic coefficients: \begin{equation} \Vert \mathbf{e}\big(N^{rs}(p) \big) \Vert_{M(\mathbf{Y})} \leq \frac{\beta}{\alpha} \end{equation}
  • Moreover, by a duality argument, it can be concluded that:
    \begin{equation} \Vert \mathbf{e}\big( \mathbf{N}^{rs}(p) - \mathbf{N}^{rs}(q) \big) \Vert_{M(\mathbf{Y})} \leq \alpha^{-1} \Vert \mathbf{C}(p) - \mathbf{C}(q) \Vert_{M(\mathbf{Y})} \Vert m_{rs} + \mathbf{e}(N^{rs}) \Vert_{M(\mathbf{Y})} \end{equation}
    From which it is possible to deduce a continuity type condition: \begin{equation} \vert C^{hom}_{ijrs}(p) - C^{hom}_{ijrs}(q) \vert \leq \Vert \mathbf{C}(p) - \mathbf{C}(q) \Vert_{lin(M(\mathbf{Y}))} \end{equation}

Contribution

On the Viscosity

Viscous Measurements

  • The presence of several tissues induces a viscoelastic behavior observed at the receptors.

  • Bernard et al 2015 studied such signals, introducing the so-called quality factors: \begin{equation} C_{ij}^* = C_{ij} + i C_{ij}' = C_{ij}(1+ Q_{ij}^{-1}), \quad i,j = 1,\dots, 6 \end{equation}

  • Such behavior can be related to a Kelvin-Voigt viscoelastic model studied by Panasenko (2008), Boughammoura (2013), and derived such factors.

Quality Factors

The obtained behavior after homogenization at frequency $\omega \in \mathbb{R}_+$ is given by: \[ \left \{ \begin{aligned} - \omega^2 \rho^0 \hat{u}^0 - \nabla \cdot \hat{\sigma}^0(\hat{u}^0) & = \mathbf{0} & \text{ in } \Omega \\ \hat{\sigma}^0 (\hat{u}^0) & = (\mathbf{C}^{hom} + \mathbf{i}\omega \mathbf{D}^{hom}):\mathbf{e}(\hat{u}^0) & \text{ in } \Omega \\ \hat{\sigma}^0(\hat{u}^0) \cdot n & = \hat{\mathbf{F}}(\omega) &\text{ in } \Gamma_N \\ \hat{u}^0 & = \mathbf{0} & \text{ in } \Gamma_D \\ \end{aligned} \right . \] where as before $\rho^0 = \int_{\mathbf{Y}}\rho(\mathbf{y}) d\mathbf{y}$ and the homogenized coefficients dependent on the complex cell solutions $N^{rs} \in \mathbf{H}^1(\mathbf{Y},\mathbb{C})$.

Decomposing the solution in its real and imaginary part, $N^{rs} = N_R^{rs} + i N_I^{rs}$ it follows then: \[ \begin{aligned} C^{hom}_{ijrs} &= \int_{\mathbf{Y}} C_{ijrs} + C_{ijkl} \mathbf{e}_{kl}(N^{rs}_R) -\omega D_{ijkl} \mathbf{e}_{kl}(N^{rs}_I) d\mathbf{y} \\ D^{hom}_{ijrs} &= \int_{\mathbf{Y}} D_{ijrs} + \omega^{-1} C_{ijkl} \mathbf{e}_{kl}(N^{rs}_I) + D_{ijkl} \mathbf{e}_{kl}(N^{rs}_R) d\mathbf{y} \end{aligned} \]

Thus, the so-called quality factors, derived from a two-scale formalism: \begin{equation} Q_{ij}^{-1} := \frac{D^{hom}_{ij}}{C^{hom}_{ij}}. \end{equation}

IV. Numerical Results

Microscale

Microscale

Elastic Results

Numerical Solutions to Cell Problems

The non-linear behavior of the homogenized coefficients is directly related to solutions of the cell problems.

Described by the unique vector-valued solutions $\mathbf{N}^{rs} \in \mathbf{H}^1(\mathbf{Y})$ for each $r,s \in \{1,\dots, d\}$ of the elliptic PDE system: \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} - \partial_{y_j}\big[C_{ijkl}(\mathbf{y}) \mathbf{e}_{kl,y}\big(\mathbf{N}^{rs}(\mathbf{y})\big) \big] = \partial_{y_j}\big(C_{ijrs}(\mathbf{y}) \big) & \quad \text{ in } \mathbf{Y} \\ \big[C_{ijkl} (\mathbf{y}) \mathbf{e}_{kl, y}\big(\mathbf{N}^{rs})(\mathbf{y}) \big) \big] n_j = \mathbf{0} & \quad\text{ on } \partial\mathbf{Y} \end{aligned} \end{equation} with average equal $\mathbf{0}$ condition.

Transverse Isotropy

  • The material coefficients are assumed over the characteristic cell in the form: \begin{equation} C_{ijkl}(\mathbf{y}) := C^m_{ijkl}\mathbb{I}_{\{ \mathbf{y} \in \mathbf{Y}_m \}} + C^f_{ijkl} \mathbb{I}_{\{\mathbf{y} \in \mathbf{Y}_p \}} \end{equation}
  • Being each component with transverse isotropic elatic behavior, describing a full elastic tensor in Voigt notation: \begin{equation} C_{ij}(\mathbf{y}) = \begin{bmatrix} C_{11}(\mathbf{y}) & C_{12}(\mathbf{y}) & C_{13}(\mathbf{y}) & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ C_{12}(\mathbf{y}) & C_{11}(\mathbf{y}) & C_{23}(\mathbf{y}) & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ C_{13}(\mathbf{y}) & C_{23}(\mathbf{y}) & C_{33}(\mathbf{y}) & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & C_{44}(\mathbf{y}) & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & C_{44}(\mathbf{y}) & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & C_{66}(\mathbf{y}) \end{bmatrix} \end{equation}
  • Simulations for 2-dimensional and 3-dimensional structures are done of the homogenized coefficients in function of the porosity level, i.e., setting the circular inclusion with radius $r(p)$ being $p \in (0,1)$ the set of admissible porosity levels in the form $p := \frac{\vert \mathbf{Y}_f \vert}{\vert \mathbf{Y} \vert}$. They are compared agains Parnell & Grimal, (2008) results.

Predictions

It is simulated with a viscous component of type $D_{ijkl}(\mathbf{y}) = \alpha^m C^m_{ijkl}(\mathbf{y}) + \alpha^f C^f_{ijkl}(\mathbf{y})$ being $\alpha^m = 5 \times 10^{-2}$ and $\alpha^f = 1 \times 10^{-3}$.

IV. Numerical Results

Mesoscale (2D)

2-Dimensional Simulations

The discretization scheme for the elastodynamic model presented uses Finite Element Method (FEM) for the space-domain while a $\beta-\gamma$ Newmark scheme for the time-domain of precision $\mathcal{O}(\Delta t)$ for parameters $\beta = 0.36 \, \gamma = 0.7$.

The simulation setting is defined by a rectangular domain imitating the experimental setup:

  1. An excitation source, defining a unique wave-guide propagation profile that characterize the porosity and thickness parameters. Enabling the generation of multiple profiles
  2. Detection is obtained by 24-72 different sensors depending on the configuration used.

Schematic Setting (2D)

Tranducer force

The force acting at the surface is modeled normal to horizontal plane of the domain surface, pointing to the mid section of the cortical bone, with central time $t_0 >0$, central frequency $f_0 > 0$ at positions $\Gamma_{u_i} \subset \Gamma_N$ in the form: \begin{equation} \mathbf{F}(\mathbf{x},t) = - e^{\frac{(t-t_0)^2}{2\sigma^2}} cos(2 \pi (t-t_0) f_0) \mathbb{I}_{\mathbf{x}\in \Gamma_{u_i}} \hat{j} \text{ on } \Gamma_N \end{equation}

Implementation done using $t_0 = 5 [\mu s]$, $\sigma_0 = 0.7 [\mu s], f_0 = 1 [MHz]$. Left side: Time plot; Right side: FFT Force.

Mesh Generation

  1. The mesh generation is done using $\texttt{CGAL}$ library, for tethaedral meshes with $40$ and $20 [\mu m]$ of mean diameter to assess the recorded signal fidelity.

  2. There is observed a clear dependence of the mesh discretization with respect to the inverse problem prediction, implying high computational costs.
    $\textbf{Mesh Size}$ $40 \,[\mu m]$ $20 \,[\mu m]$
    N° Points $\sim 30.000$ $\sim 90.000$
    N° Cells $\sim 80.000$ $\sim 300.000$

  3. Elastodynamic models are simulated for set of pairs $(Po, Th)$, evaluating the inverse problem predictions from the data recovery process.

A linear elastodynamic model is simulated using FEM discretization on space and $\beta,\gamma$-Newmark method on time, implemented with FEniCS. In this case, associated to $3.3 \, [mm]$ of tickness and $6 \%$ of porosity.

Single Source

  1. The multisource input force generates problems of computations under limited resources and time.
  2. The recording obtained from each source excitation define spacially translated wavefronts.
  3. Since the homogenized tensor is constant in space, by the symmetry of the space the setting can be reduce to just one source now adding more receptors.
  4. The simulations times ranges regarding the thickness parameter used. On a Xeon E5-2660 processor with 4 Gb. DRR3 RAM for a $20 [\mu m]$ mesh, it takes $\sim 18-26$ hrs. to describe the full simulation using 1024 time steps associated to $51.2 [\mu s]$ of real-time experimentation.

Recorded dispersion curves

Numerically simulated $(f,k)$-diagrams associated to the $L_M(f,k)$ functional. Setting of 1 source at $3.3 [mm]$ thickness and $6\%$ of porosity.

  3. Resonance in this case defines a crucial aspect in the simulations.

Eigen-frequencies

  • The eigenpairs correspond to the main cause of discontinuities observed on the dispersion curves.
  • Explicitly, defined as the sequence of pairs $\{ \lambda_k, u_k)\, :\, k \in \mathbb{N} \} \subset \mathbb{R}_+ \times \mathbf{H}^1 (\Omega, \Gamma_D)$ solution to:
    \begin{equation} \mathcal{I}_{\mathbf{C}^{hom}}(u_k,v) = \lambda_k (u_k,v)_{\Omega} \quad \forall v \in \mathbf{H}^1(\Omega, \Gamma_D) \end{equation}
  • Being the eigen-frequencies obtained in frequecy domain by the expression: \begin{equation} \lambda_k = \rho^0 (2\pi f_k)^2 \text{ i.e. } f_k = \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{\frac{\lambda_k}{\rho^0}} \quad k \in \mathbb{N} \end{equation}

The Resonances

By solving the eigen-value problem related to the elastic operator $\mathcal{C}^{hom}$ it was found the discrete spectrum related to the problem.

Frequencies related to the transductor (red) and eigen-frequencies in its neighborhood (blue).

IV. Numerical Results

Mesoscale (3D)

3-Dimensional Simulations

It is now studied the effect of radial wave behavior on the recorded signal, assessing the wave-guide propagation by cylindrical and fully irregular type domains.

  1. A Half-Cylinder domain that assess curvature effects on the recorded signal and the distortion generated from the wave interaction. It describes the first approximation of realistic bone samples from $\mu$-CT images.

  2. A rugous model retrieved from the $\mu$-CT images to assess the wave propagation now by the interior irregularities and non-uniformities naturally presented on bone samples.

Mesoscale (3D)

Half-Cylinder Model

Half-Cylinder Setting

Tetraedrical mesh defined using $\texttt{CGAL}$ with mean cell diameter of $40 [\mu m]$. Number of vertices: $\sim 170.000$; Number of cells: $\sim 956.000$. Colors indicating tagged subdomains.

Numerical Considerations

The implementation setting ressembles the 2-dimensional case, by using the same type of force at the emitters

  1. A set of 40 sensors are modelled to capture surface forces $\sigma^{hom}(u)\cdot n$ at each location generated by the propagating wave-front.

  2. The elastodynamic simulation of the homogenized transverse isotropic model with FEM and $\beta, \gamma$-Newmark scheme in FEniCS.

  3. Such simulations times ranges regarding the thickness parameter used. On a Xeon E5-2660 processor with 5 Gb. DRR3 RAM for a mesh of $40 [\mu m]$ of cell diameters, takes $\sim 25-35$ hrs. to describe a full device recordings discretize by 1024 time steps associated to $51.2 [\mu s]$ of real-time experimentation.

Mesoscale (3D)

Irregular Model

Irregular Domain Case

The half-cylinder domain simulations shows clear correspondence with the 2-dimensional case, showing the prevalence of axial-propagation over the non-axial effects that occurs during the wave-front.

It does not incorporates irregularity effects arising from the curvature nor infero-interior surfaces presented on real bone samples.

Mesh Generation

The mesh genration is done by the following data-flow procedure, by applying several layers of software. It creates a realistic complex tetrahedral mesh from a processsed volumetic image using $\texttt{CGAL}$ library.

  1. A scaling procedure from $9 \, [\mu m]$ voxel images is done to restrict memory consumption of the $\mu$-CT images stack.

  2. The stack is processed based of grayscale values regarding the materials of interest.

  3. A volumetic image is created, and parametrized to be processed with $\texttt{iso2mesh}$ library with mesh efficient mesh generation algorithms.

Mesh Generation

Data-Flow. The mesh generation involves a sequence of frameworks to optain a fully automatized procedure tjat recreates realistic meshes.

Irregular Mesh Setting

Tetrahedral Mesh with tagged subdomains describing the simulation model and characteristics.

Numerical Considerations

  1. The simulation is done over a set of 40 tagged receptors, where the resulting force $\sigma^{hom}(u)\cdot n is recorded.

  2. The Elastodynamic PDE is re-scaled to the $56 [\mu m]$ voxel length and discretized by FEM in space and $\beta-\gamma$-Newmark scheme in time.

  3. The elastodynamic model simulatied over the complex domain at $\sim 20 [\mu m]$ mean size of cell tetrahedras, requires 3 cores on a Xeon E5-2660 processor with $\sim 8 Gb$ DDR3 RAM and $\sim 7$ days of computation time.

Simulation

The wave profile similar to the Half-Cylinder case induce effects on the fast waves.

Dispersion curves

Recorded dispersion curves on the $(f,k)$-diagram of the $L_m(f,k)$ functional. Case of $11\%$ porosity and $1.8 \, [mm]$ thickness. It describes discrepancy of the reconstructed curves, explictly on the first symmetric and antisymmetric modes.

Future Objectives

  • Give a formal framework of the inverse problem formulation and well-posedness.
  • Analize the mesh irregularities and instabilities to assess interactions of the signal with the domain.
  • Obtain a viscoelastic model that fully characterize the recorded signal experimentally obtained.
  • Use adaptive mesh over the signal and reduce computational times.
    • The effects of surface curvature does not generate relevant effects on the recorded signal at the receptors. Thus, validating the conclusion obtain in the experimental fields.
    • The effects of interior irregularities of the bone, generate distorsions on the firsts modes of the recorded signal, thus on the parameter recovery process.
    • In this direction, viscoelastic behavior must be acting were damping and interaction with the traveculae.
